			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do I do when there's a stubborn warrior?<a name="15684"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 14 04 7:01 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>My initial sarcastic answer:
<br />
ctrl + d
<br />

<br />
My more useful answer:
<br />

<br />
I encounter this situation quite often, and the person in question isn't always a warrior.  I have, however, learned how to promote group survival in such a situation.  The situation, really, just boils down to multipulls that are occurring because one or more people in the group like to live dangerously.
<br />

<br />

<br />
First, I'll define the situation:
<br />

<br />
Condition One:  Uber_1337_war03 demands that he be the puller for your group (though this can apply to any situation in which someone is pulling recklessly or is just having an off day).
<br />
Condition Two:  This warrior is frequently getting pulls of four mobs (give or take a few).
<br />
Condition Three:  The group has no enchanter.
<br />
Condition Four:  You are playing a bard and are trying to keep this group alive.
<br />

<br />
Now for my disclaimer:
<br />

<br />
I do not have any inherent dislike for warriors.  I am merely formulating a strategy to combat a very specific problem that, apparently, other people have encountered as well.  
<br />

<br />
Now for the problems.  From my perspective as a bard, there are three main problems with multipulls.  They are all solveable, but the solutions are not always easy.
<br />

<br />
Problem One:
<br />

<br />
Four mobs deal about four times as much damage as a single mob does within the same period of time.  The damage is just too high to deal with!
<br />

<br />
Bardic Answer:
<br />

<br />
Melody of Mischief is your first line of defense; I keep it memorized during all LDoNs for the odd four-mob pull that I manage to get while OOM, or for multipulls that aggro the rest of my group before I have time to FM.
<br />

<br />
The procedure with MoM is simple.  Mem it, stand amidst the mobs as they pour into your party, and sing it as the first song in your twist, followed by a few songs from your regular twist.  Basically, your objective is to make sure that all of the mobs are 45% slowed until all of them have had a better, longer duration slow placed on them (read as:  you probably want to have a shaman in your group when you do this).
<br />

<br />
In most cases, this strategy is preferable to mezzing (and it is nearly always preferable to mezzing when there are five or more mobs in camp).  Reliably mezzing three mobs usually requires that the bard completely stop twisting any melee buffs.  This is tragic and cripples group DPS, especially if the bard is the main haster.  By using a PBAE slow (like MoM), a bard is still able to twist a few other songs (one very safely, two fairly safely, three riskily) to help the group out.
<br />

<br />
Also, notice that since MoM has a DoT component, mezzing the mobs affected by it won't be particularly effective except to cause a pet to get off of a bad target or to interrupt a caster.  If you're using a non-DoT PBAE slow (though I don't recommend it if you have MoM), then you can mix and match mez with it to improve your group's survivability.
<br />

<br />
Problem Two:
<br />

<br />
Four mobs have the potential to hit up to four different targets simultaneously.  This means that the cleric and wizard might soon find themselves taking a dirt nap.
<br />

<br />
Bardic Answer:
<br />

<br />
This one is tough to solve alone.  Communication is the only real way to succeed here.  This problem is easy to deal with if most of the group is willing to communicate and to work as a team, and it is a royal pain if the group is unwilling or already frustrated.
<br />

<br />
Instructions to the warrior:
<br />
I am barring asking him to let the bard pull, since that possibility has already been crossed out.  Consider asking him whether he has either Area Taunt and/or Rampage, and if he does, <i>hope</i> that he uses them when the moment is right.  If he is missing one or both, then it's no big deal.  If he's too conceited to tell you/use them, then it's still no big deal.  This is a good thing.
<br />

<br />
Instructions to rooters:
<br />
Get into tells with at least one rooter in the group (preferably not the main healer if that can be helped--a well-played shaman is, once again, a good choice) and tell him/her to be ready to do ghetto CC.
<br />

<br />
It has been my experience that rooters are <i>usually</i> where the battle to control a pulling warrior's crowd is lost or won.  If the rooters aren't cooperative, then the situation will probably be nasty, even with MoM playing.
<br />

<br />
Instructions to nukers:
<br />
Make sure that they make the main tank's target die as fast as possible when multipull's happen.  This is pretty self-explanatory and chances are good that most of them will be doing so already.
<br />

<br />
If they're bold enough to do so, don't harass nukers if they use their TAE and PBAE nukes.  Most of the time they know the consequences of getting aggro and are prepared to deal with it (by rooting, pet-tanking, etc.).
<br />

<br />
Instructions to pet classes:
<br />
Basically, make sure they're ready to pet tank stuff if the need arises, and make sure they're aware of what their pet is currently doing.  If you notice, say, that a mage's pet is getting destroyed by a mob that is already rooted, do the mage a quick favor and mez that mob to get the pet off of it.  If the pet does not immediately jump to the MT target, it's a good idea to tell the mage about it.
<br />

<br />
Against summoning mobs, it can be useful to get them rooted first, and then send in pets to eat their summons.  This occasionally causes pet deaths, but those are much better than player deaths.  Usually this isn't too much of an issue on normal.
<br />

<br />
Instructions to healers:
<br />
There's not much you can do except suggest that clerics have DA and DB memmed.  They either know what they're doing, or they don't, and the mobs will either kill them, or they won't, depending on the healers' HP/AC/etc. and how well everyone else is doing at keeping the mobs under control.
<br />

<br />
Problem Three:
<br />

<br />
Groups of four mobs do not appreciate it when bards start singing in their presence when aggro is not firmly established.  Having your songs get interrupted repeatedly is both frustrating and potentially fatal.  Here more than in other situations, you will need to be able to twist with good reliability (and you definitely don't need to die  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />).
<br />

<br />
Bardic Answer:
<br />

<br />
Above all, avoid getting hit for silly reasons.  Primarily, this means, &quot;Avoid being the closest person to a rooted mob or a group of rooted mobs.&quot;  Ideally, the warrior should fill that role.  If the mob that you're tanking isn't already rooted and it doesn't appear than anyone plans to root it anytime soon, consider firing off your deftdance macro or FM.  This will either keep you alive and leave the mob unrooted, or it will cause the mob to ping-pong onto a caster who will (hopefully) root it instinctively.
<br />

<br />
FM is also handy to protect yourself if you have &quot;low HP aggro,&quot; just make sure you stop twisting and that you're not standing next to any rooted mobs until someone heals you, or else you'll probably die when your song pulses next.
<br />

<br />
Other tips for you, the bard:
<br />

<br />
-If casters are a problem, keep the caster or casters targeted and mez them (or use Boastful Bellow AA, assuming they aren't immune) to disrupt their casting.  It's agonizing to see the MT target get CHealed while there are three other mobs wailing on your party.  Being on the receiving end of an AE rain from a holgresh in Mir really bites, too.  Psalm of Veeshan is your good buddy in dealing with this.
<br />

<br />
-Once the big slows are in place and mobs start dying, don't hesitate to drop MoM and start using mezzes.  Or, if things are quite under control already due to good rooting, then just use your combat twist.
<br />

<br />
-Kazumi's Note of Preservation is a hit-or-miss affair when trying to keep your group alive (unless the group knows about it and how to use it to the best effect).  Considering the tank's egotism, I'd say it's probably best to avoid using it.  He would likely get mad, stop paying attention to his actions, and go into a lengthy rant about how group DA screws up everyone's aggro and how the first person to click it off is guaranteed to die.
<br />

<br />
And finally, the tip that would make me slap myself if I forgot to include it:
<br />

<br />
-Crank up the DS.  Pile it high.  Get DSes on everyone in your party and watch the mobs mow themselves down.  Warsong of Zek and Psalm of Veeshan are good, good friends to have.
<br />

<br />
Okay, I'm done now.  I hope this helps someone when grouping with difficult folks.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-13.gif" border="0" alt="LOL" hspace="2" /></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Melees love us for the haste; casters love us for the mana; fleeing loonies love us for the Selo's.<br>
---Bard Motto<br>
<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=910907>Lenowill's Magelo profile</a></span></td>
